The morphological features of CDs are observed in the TEM images (Fig. 4
                        ). The as-prepared CDs exhibit a spherical shape with an average diameter of <6 nm. The size distribution is confined to a narrow range, from 3 nm to 9 nm. For PSC and PSCM nanoparticles, the predominant morphology is spherical, with uniform grain sizes and good dispersibility (Fig. 5
                        ). Additionally, the information extracted from the TEM images aligns well with the XRD analysis. The grain size distribution is illustrated in Figure S2, with the average grain diameter represented by the highest frequency in the histogram. The PSC nanoparticles have an average grain diameter of 48.62 ± 5.9 nm (Figure S2a), while PSCM nanoparticles exhibit a reduced average diameter of 31.92 ± 5.83 nm (Figure S2b). The TEM results support the XRD analysis, confirming the crystalline structure of the materials. These findings suggest that the incorporation of methylene blue enhances the ability to control the crystal size.
